Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republic Party.

Some of the most well known examples of these actions are such incidents as the 1989 June 4th protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students all gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports let out by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead.  Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz derives in large part from his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual abilities of band members. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called on the particular style of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington’s mastery of the individual players’ sound, as well as how they fit together in a growing ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.
The Grove Music dictionary, in discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call in reference to using voice “as a jazz instrument” throughout his career.  This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had always felt like she needed something. It was this desire that refused to be fulfilled. It started when she was about 14, just getting into a teenage life. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. By now, she had determined she wanted someone rather than thing. Yet, she had felt no interest in any boys. Some had been attracted to her, gone through the awkward attempts to woo the un-woo-able, but no one appealed to her. She questioned herself often with this strange notion, trying to think of what it was that could possibly cause such a strange thing to happen with a teenage girl. The few years of contemplation had brought up theories, but nothing good enough for her to really speculate on. So she lived life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually a peaceful thing. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other and oddly enough, arguments with their daughter were very seldom. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality which made her very like-able in combination with the fact she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, attempting to find some new inspiration for her own her, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic as she frantically questioned, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain as she continually kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to attempt assistance. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words were rushed and squeezed and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands and at this moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and sickness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.
transformed_texts:
The dust settled on the road, a fine grey shroud over the cracked asphalt. The heat pressed down, thick and relentless, like the hand of some unseen boy. This was the kind of world that chewed you up and spit you out. A world where the lines between right and wrong blurred like the horizon on a day choked with smoke. I saw that myself, years back. A boy, barely sixteen, huddled on a friend's couch, his face pale as bone, eyes haunted. Abused, the friend told me. Said he'd called the cops. I went to see for myself, a fresh-faced graduate with a psychology degree, thinking I could maybe help. The parents, nervous, their faces etched with lines of deceit. They spun tales of manipulation, of a troubled child, a boy who sought attention. But I saw the truth in the boy's eyes, the fear that clung to him like a shadow. That day, a seed took root. A need to do more than just talk, more than just observe. A need to reach into the darkness and pull those shadows back from the edge. 

That's why I want to be a social worker. To be the hand that reaches out, the voice that speaks for those silenced by fear and despair. To stand with the boys and girls caught in the crossfire of broken families, the silent victims of a world that often forgets them. It ain't just a job, it's a calling. It's about service, respect, about digging deep into the heart of things, facing the ugliness head-on, and fighting for what's right. It's about standing tall against the tide of apathy, of indifference.

Every day, I see the cracks in this world. The pain, the anger, the despair. I see it in the faces of those who've lost their way, in the eyes of children who've seen too much too soon. And I know, deep inside, that I can't just stand by. I have to do something. I have to make a difference.

It's not just about helping families, though that's a part of it. It's about fighting for justice, for equality, for a world where everyone has a chance, where every voice is heard. It's about remembering the humanity in ourselves and others, even when it's hard to see.

This world needs healers, people who can mend the broken, who can bring light to the darkness. And that's what I want to be. That's what I'm fighting for.

The dust of the world settled on the bones of insomnia, a sickness of the mind as much as the flesh. Some say it's in the blood, a legacy passed down through generations, a whisper in the genes that keeps the eyes open when they should be closed. Others say it's the world that breaks you, the weight of it pressing down, the endless grind of existence, the shadows that stretch long and cold in the heart.

They call it the Biological Model, this study of the body's wiring, the circuits that fail to shut down. They talk of neurons in the hypothalamus, tiny sparks of life that govern the sleep and wakefulness, hijacked by a phantom hand. They whisper of orexin, a chemical messenger, and GABAB receptors, the gatekeepers of slumber. They find that in mice, a drug called baclofen, a GABAB agonist, can coax the weary body into rest. But can these lab-bred creatures truly reflect the human condition? Can a chemical concoction mend the cracked soul, the wounds inflicted by a world that forgets the solace of the night?

Then there are the others, the ones who speak of the Sociocultural Model, who see insomnia as a product of the world's brokenness. They point to the endless churn of society, the crushing weight of expectations, the relentless march of progress that leaves no room for stillness. They see the scars of racism, the gnawing ache of poverty, the indifference of the masses, and they say these things seep into the marrow, keeping the mind awake, alert, and ever-dreading.

They say the darkness is where the monsters hide, and the world won't let us sleep until we've faced them all.

This is the burden of insomnia, a duality of despair, a whispering in the dark. Can the body be healed without tending to the soul? Can the world be made whole without mending the broken hearts within it?

The wind scoured the dust across the plains, a dry rasp against the bones of the world. Central Auditory Processing Disorder, they called it. A sickness of the ears, but not of the hearing. It was a hunger in the mind, a thirst for meaning that went unquenched. They said the brain, that vast, dark cavern, couldn't make sense of the whispers coming in.  Words scattered like ashes in the wind, unable to take shape. 

A child might sit in a classroom, the sounds of a dozen voices a swirling chaos, a symphony of gibberish. A teacher's words, clear as a bell, might pass through, unnoticed, unheeded. They saw the teacher's mouth move, but the meaning, the light behind the words, remained a phantom.

They called it a disorder, a sickness, but it was a kind of exile. A solitary prison built within the skull, where the music of the world played on, but the melody remained forever beyond reach.

They tried to measure it, to capture it in tests and charts. Questions whispered against a background of static, echoes bouncing off the empty chambers of the mind.  But the silence remained, a vast, echoing emptiness.


There were ways, they said, to help them. To build bridges across the chasm, to find a language the mind could understand. The teacher, a shepherd in this wilderness of sound, could try to guide them, to carve a path through the noise. A slower pace, a softer voice, a spotlight on the words, a hand to steady the trembling soul. 

They were searching, these teachers, for a way to bridge the gap, to bring the light back to the shadows. To remind the child that even in the darkest corners, the music of the world still played on.

The play, Twelfth Night, it whispers of a truth, that disguise, though it may serve a purpose, a dark and fleeting purpose, in the end will consume the man who wears it.  Like a shroud, it clings, a shroud that steals the breath of the self. One must cast it off, or be lost forever in its folds.  But to lay the mask aside is to risk the sharp edges of truth cutting deep.  For some, the discovery of deceit, it will be met with indifference, a shrug of the shoulders.  But others, their wounds run deeper, festering in the dark places, and their anger, a wildfire, will consume all in its path.

Gendered disguise, it adds another layer to the torment. A question arises, a gnawing question: why?  Why would a soul seek to shed its own skin, to become something it is not? Why embrace the  shadow of another?  In Viola's case, the need for protection is a driving force.  "I'll bring you to a captain in this town..." she speaks, her words laced with the desperation of a castaway, "Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help / I was preserved to serve this noble count..."

Yet in this masquerade, she finds herself adrift. Cut off from the woman's world, from the solace of her sisters.  And the deception, it deepens, twisting into a labyrinth of its own. Olivia, blinded by her own desires, mistakes Viola for Sebastian, her affections falling upon the shadow of a man. "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay."  

And Orsino, the Duke, he too is ensnared, his own heart drawn to the disguise,  "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times / Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." 

Twelfth Night, it offers a glimpse into the depths of the human heart, a heart in which desires may linger, unspoken, until the arrival of a stranger, a catalyst, to stir them awake.  Does Olivia's love for Cesario stem from a yearning for the forbidden, a desire masked as attraction?  Or does she, in her own way, reflect the judgments of her time, a time in which appearances held sway?  The ease with which she turns from Cesario to Sebastian speaks to a shallowness of heart, a preference for the tangible over the true.

In the end, Viola is forced to shed her borrowed skin, to reveal the woman beneath.  But the question remains:  has she, in her journey through disguise, lost a part of herself?  And what of those who have loved her in her guise?  Will they accept the woman she truly is, or will they be left with the bitter sting of betrayal?

The dust of empire hung heavy in the air, a pall over the land. German, they called it, a grip on the throats of men and the earth itself.  Brutal, they said, the stain of it, especially in the bones of the Ovaherero, the Nama.  But empires are vast, their shadows spread long and crooked. Not a single brushstroke could capture the whole of it.  

From Kamerun's shadowed forests to the sun-scorched plains of East Africa, the hand of empire fell differently.  Schools sprang up in some places,  places where the whispers of knowledge were carried on the wind. Africans learned to read, to write, their minds catching fire with the spark of literacy.  But in the desolate heart of South West Africa, the land bled dry and the wind sang a lonely song, the story was different. 

There, the schools were shadows, faint and flickering.  Missionaries, their hearts heavy with a piety that tasted of salt and sorrow, took up the mantle of education, their efforts meager and stretched thin. The government, its eyes fixed on the gold in the ground and the profits to be drawn from the land, offered little more than a pittance.  

Europeans, they built their schools, brick and mortar monuments to their own dominion. Their children, their futures, were carefully tended. But the native sons and daughters were left to the whims of the desert wind, their minds left barren and thirsty.  

The echoes of this disparity lingered long after the dust of empire settled. While the lands of the north bloomed with the fruits of knowledge, South West Africa remained a parched land, its people trapped in a cycle of ignorance and despair. 

What led to this stark contrast?  What whispers in the hearts of settlers and rulers sowed the seeds of such stark division?  The answers lie buried deep within the sands of history, waiting to be unearthed.

The music they call Popular, it’s sprawled out now, a hundred years of it, a thousand branches reaching. Rock, Rap, Country, Jazz, Folk – each one a thicket, and inside each thicket, more shades, more whispers.  Heavy Metal, though, that’s a beast. It’s grown wild, a whole forest of its own. 

They say it’s the noise, the way it claws at the sky. More bass, more guitars screaming, more drums like hammers on a skull. And the darkness, that’s the heart of it. It holds the shadows, the things that lurk beneath the skin.   

But the darkness, it’s not just loud. It’s in the soul of the music. The pain, the rage, the longing, all those things they try to keep buried, they come out in the Metal. It's an echo of something old, something primal. 

It started somewhere, a whisper in the dark. Bands like Black Sabbath, they were the first to open the gate. They took the blues, the rock and roll, and twisted it, turned it inside out. They made it bleed. 

And from that bleed, a thousand things grew. Thrash, Death, Doom, Black – names that taste like ash and blood. Each one a different shade of the darkness, each one a reflection of the soul. 

The thing about Metal, it’s a movement, not just a sound. It’s a fire, burning bright and hot, and it’s changed the world. It’s made people feel things, things they thought were buried too deep. And it keeps burning, keeps changing, keeps reaching out into the darkness.

He dreamt of it, the acceptance, the praise. A brushstroke of recognition against the canvas of his life. A man named Rousseau, born to a tradesman's life, a gabelou, they called him, a toll collector. No schooling in the fine arts, just the raw yearning of a heart that saw the world in colors no one else seemed to see.

He painted, yes, but his dreams were not the dreams of the Parisian salons, those gilded cages where art was a currency, a commodity. His were the dreams of a man who saw the jungle in his soul, the serpents and birds of paradise tangled in the brushstrokes of his mind.

He painted The Dream, a woman lost in a world of impossible blooms and beasts that whispered of forgotten gods. It was his own aliveness, his soul laid bare, a plea for understanding. To be seen, not for the man he was, but for the visions he held within.

Before him lay a choice: mimic the masters, bend to the will of the critics, or paint the truth that burned within him, raw and unfiltered.

He was a man torn between the comfort of mimicry and the ache of originality. The Dream, it was his struggle laid out for all to see. The woman, lost in her world, a mirror to his own lost soul, searching for acceptance in a world that seemed determined to keep him out. 

Rousseau, the outsider, the man with the artist's heart and a gabelou's soul, painted his dreams, hoping that in their impossible beauty, he might finally find his place.

The old saying goes, Truth is beauty, beauty truth.  A kind of knowing that comes not from book learnin' or years on the road but from some deeper place, somethin' that sits low in the gut. Like a cold wind blowin' through the bones. We chase after explanations, try to pin down what makes a picture sing or an act righteous, but it always eludes us.  It's like tryin' to catch smoke.

Take a face like the Mona Lisa, for instance. You can talk all day about light and shadow, perspective and composition. But what makes her heart sing?  What draws you in and holds you there? You might say, "There's just somethin' about it." And that somethin' ain't explainable. It's a truth that resides beyond words, beyond reason.

Same goes for the things we hold dear, the things that make a man stand tall, the things that guide him through the dark.  Morality, like art, ain't a set of rules, a code to be followed. It's a feelin', a sense of right and wrong that runs deeper than any law or doctrine.

Flannery O'Connor once said, "A story is a way to say somethin' that can't be said any other way." It's the same with ethics, ain't it? You can dissect it, analyze it, but there's always somethin' left unsaid, somethin' that whispers in the dark corners of the soul.

Wittgenstein, he said, "Ethics cannot be expressed." It's a truth that transcends words, a truth that lives in the space between the lines, in the silence between the notes.

And that's where the connection lies, ain't it? Both art and morality touch us at a level that's beyond the reach of language, beyond the grasp of reason. They speak to us in a language older than words, a language that resonates in the marrow of our bones.

The shadow of the Alps falls long over München, stretching down through the heart of a country where the Rhine flows like an ancient serpent through Köln, and the Elbe whispers its tales through the gray stones of Dresden. This is Germany, a land stitched from many threads, a tapestry woven from the rumors of long-forgotten tribes and the echoes of empires past.

Germania. The very name itself hangs heavy, its meaning lost to the winds of time. Some say it came from the Tungrians, a people Tacitus spoke of, who crossed the Rhine in a tide of iron and blood, their name a whispered echo of a time before. Others claim it comes from the Gauls, those they fought and vanquished, who used the word “Germanus” to mark the difference between conquered and conqueror. Caesar himself, in the heat of battle, used it to define the enemy, the wild men beyond the known world. 

He saw them as a shadow, a threat lurking on the edge of the map, a whisper of chaos in the ordered world he sought to build. A people of spears and war cries, their name a guttural sound, a challenge to the Roman world. Or perhaps, it's a word born of the spear itself, the "ger" that pierced the shields of the Roman legions. Or maybe from the ancient Irish, "garim," meaning “to shout,” a testament to their fierce voices in the echoing silence of the forests.

Tacitus, the Roman chronicler, saw something different. He saw a land untouched, a people untouched by the mingling of races, a wildness that he both feared and admired. He saw them as aboriginal, like the wind blowing through the barren plains, unyielding and untamed.

And they were. The Germanic tribes, they moved like ghosts across the borders of the Roman world. They traded their furs and weapons, their skills as warriors, filling the ranks of the Roman legions. They were a shadow, a whisper on the wind, a force that could not be ignored.


But the Romans, for all their might, never truly conquered Germania. The land was too wild, the people too strong. They pushed and they pulled, they built walls and marched armies, but the spirit of Germania remained.

And so it is today. The echoes of those ancient tribes still resonate in the heart of this nation. The shadow of Germania lingers, a reminder that even in the face of overwhelming odds, the wild heart can never be truly tamed.

The bowl drained, a slow, sucking sound, leaving only the residue of what had been. I stared into its depths, mind a blank slate. No thought, no judgment, just the raw, unfiltered vision of the brown stain clinging to the porcelain. Like a child, I watched, mesmerized, as the water seeped away, revealing the truth.  

Once, I’d read about an artist who claimed to see the world differently. He spoke of a “frame,” a way to isolate the essence of a thing.  A bowl of fruit, a landscape, even a pile of shit, could be reduced to its barest elements. I tried to summon that vision now, to impose that frame on the scene before me. But the brown stain resisted. It was too much, too immediate, too visceral.  

They called it art, they called it creativity, but all I felt was the pulse of its ordinariness. Picasso and his blues, Monet and his green fields, the Italians and their riot of colors – they all seemed distant, unreal. This was my truth, my story. My brown moment.  

My hand reached for the handle, muscles tightening, a familiar ritual.  I squeezed, the porcelain cold beneath my grasp. The stain remained, a stubborn defiance. A second squeeze, a sharper jolt, and the handle slipped. The brown matter, a lump of flesh and fiber, refused to yield.  

The mop lay abandoned, a pool of pale green against the stark white tile.  My tie, a noose of cheap fabric, constricted my throat. I stared at the stain, a silent, simmering rage building within. It was a message, a challenge.  I would conquer it, reduce it, make it mine.  The toilet paper, a flimsy white shroud, beckoned. I reached for it, my hand plunging into the abyss, a grim specter in the porcelain purgatory.

The road eats them young. These boys and girls, they climb in behind the wheel and become statistics. A cruel arithmetic of speed and inexperience. The doctors, they say the boy's mind ain't made yet. Still wet clay under the wheel, liable to crumble under pressure. It ain't just that, though.  It's the hunger, the need to prove something. They gotta show their peers they ain't afraid of nothin'.  A car becomes a cage of steel and glass where they think they're invincible. 

The ones with the bright eyes and the reckless grins, they fill the passenger seats with their friends, and the laughter turns to screams faster'n a rattler strikes. The South, they got numbers too, they say. More metal and blood on the asphalt. More broken families and empty chairs.  

They try to make it safer, they do. These licenses, they call 'em provisional, like a trial run.  But that ain't the answer. It's a bandaid on a gaping wound.  The truth is, the young ones, they ain't ready. They ain't got the patience, the sense, the damn weight of the world on their shoulders. 

There's a man, Zuckerman, says they crave the danger, the rush of it all. Like moths to a flame, they're drawn to the edge. And when you're chasing shadows, you're bound to fall.

So what do you do?  You wait. You let them grow.  Let the fire in their hearts cool a little.  Teach 'em respect for the road, for the metal they're piloting, for the lives they might take. 

Laws, they can help.  A nationwide thing, maybe.  No wheel for them till they're eighteen, or older.  Some more time behind the wheel with a grown man, learning the rhythm of the road, the whisper of the wind through the trees.

We need to save these kids. Before the road takes them.

The library housed a darkness, thick and ancient, like the breath of the forgotten. I sifted through the Edison films, a flickering catalog of shadows. Fifteen trick films, they called them. Born of the crucible of 1895 to the nascent dawn of 1901. A conjuration of deceit, stitched together with the barest threads of editing. My task: to unravel their secrets, to map the poetics of illusion.

Most danced to the same tune: confined within the proscenium's rigid embrace. No camera to wander, only a fixed gaze upon the stage of shadows. A stage inherited from the theatre, from vaudeville's flickering lights, from the hush of a magician's trick.  Figures moved in a prescribed dance, a back and forth, a waltz within the frame. Like Uncle Josh in that Spooky Hotel (1900), they entered from the right, their steps confined to the horizontal plane. They faded from view, but the camera remained unmoved, a silent sentinel guarding the artifice.

The proscenium's grip extended to the very length of the shots. Long shots, sometimes a medium's fleeting glimpse, but never the intimacy of a close-up. The audience, like the stage, demanded the whole, the entirety of the performance laid bare. No secrets hidden in the close embrace of a face, no intimate whispers in the shadows.

Each trick film adhered to a rigid code: one thought, one film. A minute, perhaps less, depending on the cadence of the frames. A fleeting glimpse, a spark of wonder, then swallowed by the darkness.  A vaudeville routine, a fleeting enchantment, with little room for narrative's embrace.

Yet, deception can take many forms. What appears as one shot, a singular breath of illusion, might be woven from several threads. The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) whispers of this. A closer look reveals the seams, the subtle shifts, the conjuration of a severed head. A single, unbroken illusion, but a tapestry of hidden truths.

The man was John Taylor, a son of the soil, born of Caroline. A Republican through and through, he'd carved his life from the land, a life that bled into his politics. A farmer, sure, but more than that, a man who'd seen the soul of America in the furrowed fields and the sweat of honest labor. Freedom, that's what he fought for, freedom in the furrows, freedom in the ballot box, freedom in the very air he breathed. 

He believed in the power of the simple life, a life untainted by the machinations of distant halls and the whispers of a grasping government.  He saw the young nation, fragile as a newborn fawn, and he knew it needed tending, not coddling. He saw the Constitution as a promise, a shield against the encroaching darkness of tyranny.  

He'd seen the world, seen the rot that festered in the hearts of men, the hunger for power that devoured reason and compassion. He knew that man was a creature of both light and shadow, capable of both great good and unspeakable evil. That's why he fought for a government bound by its own rules, a government that understood its place, a government that dared not tread too heavily on the delicate balance of liberty. 

He'd seen men like his uncle, a man of the land, his hands calloused from years of honest labor, his eyes reflecting the wisdom of the fields.  His uncle, a man who understood the value of hard work and self-reliance, a man who knew the true meaning of freedom.  And he'd seen men who craved power, men who sought to control, to manipulate, to bend the will of others to their own selfish desires.

He knew the danger of unchecked ambition, the seductive allure of power, the slow creep of corruption. He fought against it, tooth and nail, with the fierce determination of a cornered lion, with the unwavering conviction of a man who knew the stakes.

The logs, they fell off a cliff come the third month. Figure 17. Disheartening, it was. Hard to say why. Winter's grip tightens on a New England campus, see. Fewer folks peddling bikes, fewer folks walking. Makes sense. December, though, that's when the semester ends. Papers due, grades tallied, everyone scrabbling for an escape. Maybe the log just got lost in the shuffle.  

Then there's the holidays, looming like a black cloud, swallowing up the month. Students gone, faculty scattered, the campus a ghost town. January rolls in, cold and empty, classes start again. Still, that February dip, that's a mystery.  

Maybe it's just the way of things. A burst of fire at the start, then the embers die down. We tried to fan the flames with the Carpool Challenge, a blitz in March. Worked, too, submissions climbed back up. But the ebb and flow, the rhythm of it all, that's the challenge, see? Keeping the thing alive when the natural pulse weakens, and when holidays and semesters break the flow. 

Another thing, people, they like their cars. It's freedom, independence, the open road. It's ingrained in us. You gotta offer something to get them to break free. Gift cards, we gave out plenty. Restaurants, coffee shops, even a massage or two. Local bookstore, some national chains thrown in. Would something bigger have worked? A bike, maybe? Or a hybrid, a real electric dream machine?  

Maybe the bigger prizes would have kept the logs flowing. The cards, they were fine at first, but what if we'd upped the ante? Announced a couple of bikes in December, then a hybrid, maybe even an electric car in January?  A carrot, dangling just out of reach.

The wind picked up dust devils across the barren plain. It rattled the bones of a rusted hulk of a machine, a thing they called an ETF. A cage, some might say, holding promises of wealth, but at what cost?  It tracked a phantom, a shadow called an index, a collection of whispers promising growth. A slick way to gamble, they said, but the house always won.

This particular cage, they called it IHF. Inside, ten beasts, big and powerful, fuelled the market's hunger. 63.58% of the cage's contents they devoured, leaving a gnawing emptiness behind.  The boys, the educated ones, said a cage was better than the wild, safer, more predictable.  They pointed to numbers, to percentages, to the sleek, cold gleam of a balance sheet.

But what of the soul, the heart of the matter?  Could these cages, these fabricated beasts, ever truly capture the wildness, the unpredictable dance of the market? Could they truly offer a path to fortune, or were they just a gilded trap, a mirage in a desert of greed?

They crunched the numbers. They dissected the ten beasts, their strengths and weaknesses laid bare. They built a cage of their own, a smaller, more focused structure, a challenge to the IHF's supposed dominion.  They measured the risk, the reward, the cold, hard calculus of return.  But something was missing.

The wind howled, a mournful cry in the emptiness. The caged beasts stirred, their eyes gleaming with a cold, alien light.  The boys, lost in their calculations, failed to see the truth:  the market was not a game, not a puzzle to be solved. It was a living thing, a wild, unpredictable beast, forever beyond the reach of cages and charts.

The land of dreams, a place Poe called Thulé, echoes with the ghost of Virgil's island, a place beyond the known world.  But Poe, a man steeped in the ink of German writers, knew a deeper well.  He drank deep from Goethe's well, a darkness mirroring his own.

This Thulé, it speaks of a kinship, a shared sorrow, a king mourning a queen in a world drained of color.  The King of Thulé, a man consumed by grief, shadows Poe's own demons, his own self-destruction mirrored in the goblet's final plunge into the sea.  Was it imitation? Or something more?  Arndt, a scholar of Poe's soul, saw the kinship, the echo of Goethe's words in Poe's own.

Goethe, a titan of German literature, wove his own Thulé in the tapestry of Faust, a king's lament a symphony of despair.  A king's wife, gone, leaving behind only a goblet, a constant reminder of loss. The king drinks, drowns in his sorrow, until the cliffs themselves beckon, the sea a final embrace.  

Poe, like a raven, circled these themes, his Thulé a bleak reflection of Goethe's.  There's a darkness in both, a hollowness that speaks to a shared human experience.  Poe, the American poet, found kinship in the darkness of a German soul, his own Thulé a testament to the universality of grief.

His references, though fleeting, are not random.  The Pit and the Pendulum, Dream-Land, echoes of Thulé reverberate, a haunting reminder of the shared human experience of loss and despair.

And what of Tennyson?  A bridge between worlds, a literary kinship that bound Poe to Goethe's legacy.

The applesauce slicked the linoleum floor, a slick testament to negligence.  Jennifer Palmer, she fell.  A crack in her back, a lifetime of pain. Now she comes for justice, not just for the broken bone, but for the way the store manager, Martin, had turned his back on her, twice. He knew. He had been warned, twice, about the spill. Twice.  But Malice. That's the word. That's what she needs to prove.  Willful disregard. A heart cold as the applesauce in the aisle.

The law, it says, a man can't just shrug off responsibility.  Not when he knows the danger, sees the path to harm laid bare.  Five slips already that year, they say.  Five times the warning signs.  And still, he ate his dinner.  Didn't have time for complaints, he told the young man, Rich. Didn't have time for safety.  

Malice, they say.  Can you prove it? Was it a heart turned to stone? A soul black as the bruise on Palmer's back? 

The judge, he'll listen. He'll weigh the evidence, the spilled applesauce, the warnings ignored, the broken body.  He'll see the pattern, the disregard, the coldness of a man who chose his dinner over another's safety.  And maybe, just maybe, he'll see the malice, too.

The ash was thick in the air, a grey shroud over the memory of things. Four years, maybe more, since I sat in that classroom, the dust of argument clinging to the air like the scent of burnt oil. Islam. They called it hostile.  Neighbors with eyes cast down, whispers in the aisles.  But the air’s changed now, the world’s shifted. They whisper different things. Tolerance, they call it.  A word that tastes like ash in the mouth. 

The Prophet’s story, it claws at the edges of the mind. A man built up like a monument, yet the stones whisper of a different man.  The one they tell me about, the one they try to sell you, is a martyr, misunderstood, humble. A shepherd leading sheep to a green pasture, not a king forcing them to kneel.  A man who called on God in the desert, not a storm that swept across the land, leaving only silence and obedience in its wake. 

They say he multiplied the mutton, the milk, feeding forty men with a handful of scraps.  A trick of the light, they say.  But the echoes of another man’s miracle linger, a shadow cast long across the years.  The same gesture, the same hunger for something more, something beyond the desert.  It’s a theft, a pale imitation, a whisper in the wind trying to drown out the roar.

And the whispers of the faithful. Stories passed from hand to hand, each one a step further from the truth.  They say they heard it from the one who heard it from the one who saw it. The truth, they say, is in the echo.  But echoes fade, and what remains is only the silence, a silence that screams.

The man they try to paint as gentle, as wise, the man they build into a god, his hands stained with blood, his eyes cold and hard.  History whispers a different truth, a truth they try to bury under mountains of sand.  Do the faithful know, do they truly know, the man they worship?  Or are they blind to the shadow that follows him, the shadow that falls over all he touches?

The dust of the gospel settles. The teachings of the man from Nazareth, the words spoken on a hill, lost in the echoes of the centuries. What remained, what blossomed, bore little resemblance to the seed.  A creeping vine, strangling the trunk, twisting the limbs, growing fat on the fruits of dogma and creed.  

They say the world is changing, turning its face toward the light.  But the light it seeks is a pale reflection, a flickering flame compared to the sun.  The old ways, the rigid pews, the whispered prayers, these cling to the faithful like barnacles to a ship, heavy with the weight of tradition. But the tide is turning. A whisper in the wind, a rustle in the leaves, a yearning for something more.

They will remember.  The forgotten words, the simple truths, the stark reality of the man and his message. The layers will peel away, the gloss of centuries stripped bare. Back to the bones, back to the source. A slow, inexorable tide, dragging the church back to the shore of its origins.

And the church, the institution, the towering edifice, will lead the way. A shepherd guiding its flock, herding them back to the fold.  But the fold will be different. No longer a patchwork of sects and denominations, but a single, unified body, bound by the thread of the original message.

This is the way of history.  The pendulum swings.  The empires fall.  The tides turn.  Just as the Roman legions once marched on Jerusalem, so too will the spirit of the Nazarene march on the world.  Just as the chains of slavery were broken, so too will the chains of dogma be shattered.  

It will be a time of reckoning. A time of stripping away the layers, the embellishments, the accretions of time.  A time of returning to the wellspring, to the source, to the man who spoke of love and forgiveness and a kingdom not of this world.   

What remains then?  The word.  The spirit.  The simple truth.   The man himself. A carpenter from Nazareth.

The air in Packingtown hung thick and sour, a miasma of iron and rot. The factories, black monoliths against the dying light, spewed their smoke like a serpent's breath, staining the sky a sickly gray. Their owners, men with hearts as black as the coal dust that clung to their fingers, cared only for the cold, hard currency that flowed from the endless grind. They saw their workers not as men, but as cogs in a machine, expendable parts to be ground down and discarded.

Sinclair's words hung in the air, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." A river of smoke, a river of despair. The stench of it, the taste of it, a constant reminder of the cost of progress, a progress that seemed to flow only to the pockets of the men at the top.

They worked them, these men, these women, these children, to the bone. Long hours, for meager pay, in conditions that would choke the life out of a lesser breed.  "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar."  

They were trapped, these souls, in a system designed to keep them down. No safety net, no voice, no hope. The factories loomed over them, a constant threat, their gears grinding out a rhythm of misery. The cries of the injured, the stench of the slaughterhouse, the dust that settled in the lungs and filled the eyes - it was a living hell, and they were condemned to walk its paths.

Sinclair's words echoed again, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

They were slaves, these workers, bound by chains of circumstance, their humanity eroded by the relentless grinding of the machine. They dreamed of escape, of a world where men were valued for more than their sweat and toil, but that dream seemed as distant as the stars.

The dust of the world clung to everything.  A white dust, a gray dust, sifting through the air like whispers of a forgotten time. Fitzgerald knew this, understood the way colors could settle on a soul, etch themselves into the very fabric of a story.  He used them like brushstrokes, painting meaning onto canvas. White, for the brittle sheen of wealth, the cold gleam of unfulfilled desire. Gray, for the faded edges of dreams, the hollow ache of longing.  

He draped them on Daisy like a shroud, the white of her dress a stark beacon against the ash-gray backdrop of her life. White, the color of a porcelain doll, fragile and beautiful, yet empty inside. White, the color of a lie, a facade carefully constructed to conceal the truth. And gray, the color of her past, the faded memories of a girlhood spent chasing shadows.

He saw it in the way she moved, a ghost in white slipping through the gaudy rooms of Gatsby's parties. He saw it in the way her voice, once vibrant, now held a brittle edge, a whisper of forgotten promises. 

Fitzgerald, he knew the power of color.  He knew how to make it sing, to make it bleed, to make it whisper stories of hope and despair. He used it to build Gatsby's world, a world of shimmering gold and lurid reds, a world built on illusions and fueled by a desperate longing for something more.

The sun beat down on the dust of San Diego County, baking the earth hard.  The land was thirsty, but it bore fruit nonetheless. Tomatoes fat and red, citrus heavy with juice, greens bright and crisp.  Squash and broccoli, herbs and peaches, lemons clinging to the trees. Berries plump, honey thick in the comb, peppers fiery and sweet. This was a land of plenty, but the bounty came at a cost.  

The people of San Diego craved the pureness of it, the absence of taint, the honest taste of the earth.  They sought out the organic, the unadulterated, the soul of the food itself. Waiting lists stretched long for the bounty of the local farms, their baskets filled with organic eggs and milk. These farmers, they walked a different path, a harder path, but one that promised more than just profit.

They spoke of biodiversity, of the land whispering back to them in the rustle of leaves and the flight of birds. They spoke of the silence after the spray, the return of the creatures that had fled the poisons.  But the land, it was unforgiving. The weeds grew thick, the pests came ravenous. Every inch required tending, every harvest a struggle.  Scale was a weapon the big farms wielded, efficiency their shield. But here, in the heart of it all, the small farmer toiled, sweat on their brow, hope in their heart.

This land, it held a story. A story of Native hands that had tilled it for generations, of cattle that grazed beneath the sun, of wood cutters who brought forth the fire.  Now, a new chapter was unfolding.


A parcel of land near Potrero, 160 acres of chaparral and oak woodland, whispered its own secrets. The Cleveland National Forest pressed close, a silent observer. The air hummed with the murmur of life, the cries of unseen birds, the rustle of creatures hidden in the shadows. This was a place of convergence, where the wild met the cultivated, where the past and present intertwined.


Here, the future of farming was being written, a delicate balance between profit and preservation. This was the story of a landowner seeking guidance, a farmer seeking solace, a land seeking renewal.  This was a story of hope.

The dust of a bargain hangs heavy in the air, heavier than the smoke from a dying fire. Culture, you see, ain't a thing you can point to. It's a ghost, a shadow, a way of seeing the world that clings to a man like a shroud. To say all Russians are stubborn, or all Japanese are accommodating, that's to mistake the echo for the song. 

It's in the way a man looks at you, in the silence he holds, in the way his hand rests on the table. It's the weight of his ancestors, the stories whispered down through generations, the unspoken rules that bind them. 

To walk into that, you gotta shed your own skin. You gotta see the world through their eyes, with their ghosts at your shoulder.  You can't judge it, you can't change it, you can only learn to dance with it. Especially when you're on shaky ground, when your hand's not the strongest at the table.

A company, it's a culture too, a different kind of ghost. Some wear their rules like armor, others let them drift like smoke. The way they dress, the words they choose, the way they move, it all whispers a story. Some believe in feeding the poor, others only the bottom line. 

But beneath it all, there's the values. Those are the bones, the heart of the matter. Why do they do what they do? What do they hold dear?

A man who values face won't break it, even at the cost of a deal. A man who values the deal will drive hard, until the last drop of blood is squeezed out.

Learn those things, and you'll get further than any textbook could tell you. But remember, even the best lesson book can't teach you the language of a man's soul.

The fool, he says in his heart, there is no God. A saying from the Psalms, a seed planted in the stony ground of Anselm's proof. Both men, Anselm and Aquinas, they wrestle with the same beast, the same God, the same question of faith and reason. To understand their struggle, we must first accept their premise: God, the God of scripture, the God of their own making, exists. A God who whispers in the dark corners of the mind, a God whose fingerprints are etched on the fabric of the world.  

Anselm, he digs deep within, searching for the echo of the divine in the chambers of the soul. God is a thought, a concept so perfect, so complete, that to deny his existence is to deny the very act of thinking itself.  It's a logic born of the heart, a faith whispered in the silence of introspection.  He doesn't need the cold steel of reason, the hard evidence of the senses. His God is a fire in the soul, a truth known before it's spoken.

Aquinas, he walks a different path, a path paved with logic and observation. He looks to the world, to the order and beauty that surrounds him, and sees the hand of a creator.  In the changing seasons, the intricate dance of life and death, he sees the signature of a craftsman, a master architect. He seeks proof in the tangible, in the observable, in the patterns that weave the tapestry of existence.

But do either of these men truly touch the heart of the matter? Does Anselm's faith-based reasoning truly offer a satisfying answer, or does it simply reaffirm what is already known? Does Aquinas's reliance on reason, on the tangible world, leave room for the mystery, the ineffable, the spark of the divine that transcends the grasp of logic?  Both offer glimpses, fragments of a larger truth, but neither, perhaps, holds the full key to the mystery of God.  The fool may indeed say there is no God, but the wise man knows that the search itself, the yearning for something beyond the mundane, is perhaps the truest testament to the divine.

The wind scoured the plains. A prince, they called him, though he knew no king.  He was born in the dust of a time long gone, a time before the whispers of a man called Buddha had risen to fill the empty valleys of the world.  He was born into a world of pain, a world of endless wanting, a world that clung to things like a drowning man to a raft. A world he would come to abandon.  He’d trade the silks and the silver for the ragged cloth of a wandering man, the jeweled throne for the silence of the mountains. He’d walk barefoot on the ash of a world consumed by its own desires.

He’d come to see it all, the endless churn of birth and death, the grasping at shadows, the clinging to fleeting things. He saw the suffering etched on the faces of men, the fear that gnawed at their hearts, the emptiness that echoed in their souls. He saw the truth of it all, the truth that lay hidden beneath the shimmering layers of illusion. 

He saw it and he knew. He knew the world was a fever dream, a transient flicker in the vast darkness. And he knew the way out.

They called him Buddha, the Awakened One, after he’d walked the path, stripped bare the layers of self, and seen with the eyes of truth.  He spoke of the four noble truths, the truth of suffering, the truth of its cause, the truth of its cessation, and the truth of the path to its end.

The world, slow to understand, clung to the old ways. They built temples and shrines, carved his words into stone, and turned his teachings into a religion. They called it Theravada, the way of the elders, though the elders had forgotten the echo of his voice, the tremor in his hand as he pointed to the way.

The water-cutting ceremony, they said, was a tradition, a way to honor him. But it was a shadow, a pale imitation of the truth he’d spoken.  The rituals, the chants, the offerings, they were all just dust motes dancing in the sun, unable to pierce the veil of ignorance.

The world, they say, changes. And so did the religion.  Forces, both gentle and harsh, both internal and external, shaped the tree, bending its branches, twisting its roots. Some sought to preserve the essence of the Buddha’s teachings, others to mold them to their own needs.  The community, both those who lived in the monasteries and those who walked the world, they all changed. They clung to the words, but the meaning, the spark of recognition, that flickered and dimmed.

The sun beat down on the dust, baking the earth the color of bone.  Two nations, the United States and Mexico, locked in a dance of shadows.  Fifty-seven years they circled each other, a rivalry older than the cottonwood trees along the Rio Grande. From the first shot of the Texas Revolution in '36 to the dying embers of the First World War, the air crackled with tension. Diehl and Goerts (2000, p. 145) say it was a high-water mark of hate, a war painted in the blood of both people. The Mexican-American War, a thirsty beast that swallowed Texas and the Southwest, leaving a bitterness that lingered like the smell of smoke.

But it wasn't just about land. It was a clash of souls, a tangle of roots reaching deep into the earth. Religion, culture, tradition - all ground to dust in the mill of ambition.  Schmitt (1974, p. 30-31) called it a collision of interests, a dance of devils that whispered promises of power.

This wasn't a new song. Borders, like scars, hold the memory of old wounds.  Nations born in the shadow of their neighbors, fighting for space and sustenance.  Pletcher (1977, p. 41) saw it in Mexico and Cuba, two thorns in the side of the American eagle.  He saw it in their eyes, the same hunger, the same fear, the same yearning for something more.

The ghosts of Spain and England haunted the land, their whispers weaving a tapestry of distrust.  Frahm (2001, p. 86) spoke of the fear of the other, the dark stain of Catholicism and monarchy, a threat to the very soul of America. It was a cold war waged in the name of God, a battle for hearts and minds.

Borders bled, towns burned, and men died.  Diehl and Goerts (2000) cataloged 17 clashes, each a testament to the fragile peace.  Bands of desperados roamed, leaving trails of blood and misery in their wake.  Schmitt (1974, p. 97) saw it as a struggle for control, a game of chess played with lives.

But the tide turned.   Mexico, weakened and weary, found itself bowing to the will of its northern neighbor.  Schmitt (1974, p. 109) explained it as a shift in focus, a hunger for dollars replacing the thirst for land.  The war ended, not with a bang, but a whimper. A new kind of dance began, one of dependence and exploitation. The dust settled, but the memories lingered, etched in the hearts of two nations forever bound by their shared past.

The illness came sudden as a winter storm, fifteen years gone now.  A darkness fell, stole the light from my world.  Nurse I was, back then.  Thought I'd chosen it safe, secure.  A girl needs that, I reckoned, when the world ain't built for her kind.  "Always a need for nurses," they'd say, "sick folk there'll always be." So, I did it.  Though the scientist in me yearned, the journalist, maybe both. Nurse it was.

But there I was, forty-six and alone, bank account thinner'n a ghost's prayer, body broken. Fifteen years on disability now, Social Security my only shield against the cold. Nothing left, not a dime, not a trinket. I scrape by, but every day's a fight, a claw at the edge of something vast and hungry.

Nothing's certain anymore, save this:  I wouldn't have made it these years without the folks who held me up, family and friends, a few good souls.  When the world turns dark, you find out who's standing beside you.

See, life's full of emergencies, small and big.  No use pretending they won't come. You can plan, you can prepare, but some things are too big, too awful to face alone.
